text: Neck Airway Injuries Management COMMON EPA June 03, 2025 Bridget Olsen, MD • Ryan Meehan, MD • Damien Carter, MD Based on a previous module by Brian J. Eastridge, MD, and Vincent Chong, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy The neck is divided into 3 zones from inferior to superior including 2 triangles. Zone I, sternal notch to the cricoid cartilage, includes subclavian vessels, internal jugular veins, proximal carotid arteries, vertebral arteries, apices of the lung, trachea, esophagus, spinal cord, thoracic duct, and thyroid gland. Zone II, cricoid cartilage to angle of the mandible, includes common carotid arteries and their branches, vertebral arteries, jugular veins, trachea, larynx, esophagus, pharynx, spinal cord, vagus nerves, and recurrent laryngeal nerves. Zone III, angle of the mandible to base of the skull, includes the distal internal carotid arteries, vertebral arteries, jugular veins, pharynx, spinal cord, and cranial nerves IX through XII. Anterior triangle of the neck is bounded by the sternocleidomastoid (SCM) muscle, lower border of the mandible, and the anterior cervical midline. Posterior triangle of the neck is bounded by the posterior aspect of the SCM muscle, the clavicle, and the trapezius muscle. The esophagus lies directly posterior to the trachea within the pretracheal fascia, which descends from the larynx into the mediastinum. Patterns of Injury Epidemiology Aerodigestive tract injuries are rare but potentially life threatening. Penetrating mechanisms are more likely than blunt mechanisms to cause either tracheobronchial or pharyngoesophageal injuries, with some studies reporting a 10- to 20-fold greater incidence. Patients with tracheobronchial injuries often die before they can be transported to a trauma center. The estimated incidence of traumatic tracheobronchial injury is 2% to 3%. Penetrating injury to the neck is associated with an approximate 5% incidence of esophageal injury. Outcomes Tracheobronchial injury can be associated with life-threatening airway loss, asphyxia, hemorrhage, aspiration, and tension pneumothorax. Penetrating laryngotracheal trauma mortality is 20%. Pharyngoesophageal injury can be associated with aspiration and delayed mediastinal or thoracic infection. Delayed recognition of pharyngoesophageal injuries and subsequent infection is the leading cause of delayed death from neck trauma. Mortality is as high as 22%; morbidity and mortality increases if diagnosed more than 24 hours after presentation. Evaluation and Initial Management Initial management First determine if the patient is unable to breathe or hard signs of aerodigestive tract injury or vascular injury are present. Hard signs of aerodigestive tract injury include air bubbling from a penetrating wound, active hemorrhage (ie massive hemoptysis or hematemesis, pulsatile or expanding hematoma), significant subcutaneous emphysema, and significant respiratory distress. If the patient is unstable or stable with hard signs, perform advanced trauma life support (ATLS), secure the airway, assess for other life-threatening injuries, and do rapid surgical exploration. In patients with blunt trauma and concern for tracheal injury, ensure successful ventilation with a bag valve mask before rapid sequence intubation (RSI). Paralysis can result in loss of airway and respiratory demise. A blowing air or “sucking” wound can indicate tracheal injury. Patients can rapidly decompensate during intubation and may require a

surgical airway (or, if able, secure the airway in the OR). Soft signs of aerodigestive tract injury include proximity of injury to the trachea and esophagus, mild subcutaneous emphysema, pneumomediastinum, mild hemoptysis or hematemesis, dysphagia, and dysphonia. CTA evaluates for potential neurovascular and aerodigestive tract injury. Thin-slice CT has high sensitivity for detecting laryngotracheal injuries. Temporizing measures include digital occlusion of hemorrhaging vessels or placement of a Foley catheter in the wound (clamped). Place intravascular lines on the contralateral side. Notes on further workup Patients with unexplained subcutaneous or mediastinal emphysema or other clinical signs of airway injury should be evaluated further with laryngoscopy and bronchoscopy. CT is less sensitive for identifying pharyngoesophageal injuries, with some reports noting sensitivity as low as 53%. However, CT imaging can show trajectories of penetrating injuries and associated pneumomediastinum, which require further imaging. For suspected esophageal injuries, esophagoscopy and contrast studies are complementary. The combination of esophagoscopy and esophagography (water-soluble contrast followed by thin barium) provides almost 100% sensitivity. Grading American Association of the Surgery of Trauma: Grade I: contusion, hematoma, or partial-thickness laceration Grade II: laceration ≤50% of circumference Grade III: laceration ≥50% of circumference Grade IV: segmental loss or devascularization ≤2 cm Grade V: segmental loss or devascularization ≥2 cm Schaefer classification for tracheal injuries: Grade 1: Minor endolaryngeal hematomas or lacerations without detectable fractures Grade 2: More severe edema, hematoma, minor mucosal disruption without exposed cartilage, or nondisplaced fractures Grade 3: Massive edema, large mucosal lacerations, exposed cartilage, displaced fractures or vocal cord immobility Grade 4: More severe massive edema, large mucosal lacerations, exposed cartilage, displaced fractures or vocal cord immobility with disruption of the anterior larynx, unstable fractures, ≥2 fracture lines, or severe mucosal injuries Grade 5: Complete laryngotracheal separation Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Positioning The patient should be supine with a shoulder roll; prep the neck and full chest in case of sternotomy or thoracotomy. Lateral decubitus is another option for stable patients with known distal esophageal injuries; however, in the setting of trauma, this position is not commonly used. Incision placement should be based on injury location for the best exposure. Basic tenets of surgical repair for aerodigestive tract injuries Due to the segmental vascular supply to both the trachea and esophagus, mobilization should be done only for adequate debridement and a tension-free repair or anastomosis. Basic principles for repair include: Debriding nonviable tissue Identifying the full extent of mucosal injury Undertaking primary repair for less than 50% circumferential injury for esophageal injuries (<1/3 for tracheal) Undertaking segmental resection and anastomosis for more than 50% circumferential injury Doing a tension-free repair Buttressing the repair with available muscle, pericardium, or pleura (helps strengthen the repair and decrease the risk for fistula) Ensuring contamination control For high-grade esophageal injuries or in patients with hemodynamic instability, performing proximal diversion with a cervical esophagostomy and distal esophageal ligation may be necessary. Most tracheal injuries

are related to penetrating injuries with minimal tissue loss. In these cases, a single layer interrupted 3-0 monofilament absorbable suture can be used for a primary repair. Protective tracheostomy: done for crush injuries to the trachea, tears more than 1/3 of the circumference, major laryngeal injuries, and when needed for other reasons (eg, expected prolonged ventilatory support).

Hand Injuries UNCOMMON March 14, 2025 Ravi F. Sood, MD • Ashleigh M. Francis, MD • Simon G. Talbot, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Indications and Contraindications In a patient with hand trauma, be able to examine the extremity and determine if there is injury to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS), flexor digitorum profundus (FDP), and/or extensor tendon. FDS function is assessed by asking the patient to flex the finger at the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint while holding the other fingers in extension. FDP function is assessed by asking the patient to flex the finger at the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint while holding the PIP joint in extension. Extensor tendon function is assessed by asking the patient to extend a finger against resistance with the terminal extensor and central slip acting to extend the DIP and PIP joints, respectively. Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-11. Individual clinical testing of the flexor digitorum profundus (A), flexor digitorum superficialis (B), flexor pollicis longus (C), finger extensors (D), and thumb extensors (E). In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to explain how timing may affect which operation is selected and required to achieve successful repair. Immediate (< 24 hours) or delayed primary (within 2 weeks) repair is ideal when possible. If there is a longer interval between injury and repair, tendon grafting or tendon transfer may be necessary. Rehabilitation protocols must balance the risk of rupture against the risk of adhesion formation and stiffness. Operative Anatomy In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to identify the basic neurovascular anatomy, tendon anatomy, and pulley anatomy required to avoid injury to these structures. The FDS tendon divides into two slips (Camper chiasm) and inserts on the volar aspect of the middle phalanx. The FDP tendon passes through the FDS tendon just proximal to the FDS insertion and inserts distally on the volar aspect of the distal phalanx. The neurovascular bundles run on the radial and ulnar aspects of each finger, with the nerve lying volar to the artery in the finger and dorsal to the artery in the palm. The flexor tendon sheath, which contains the flexor tendons in the finger, is made up of thicker, firmer annular pulleys A1 to A5 and thinner, more compressible cruciate pulleys C1 to C3. The A2 and A4 pulleys, which overlie the proximal and middle phalanges respectively, are most important to prevent bowstringing during finger flexion. In a patient with a known tendon injury, be able to name the zones of injury—especially as these pertain to treatment. Flexor tendon injuries are categorized into five anatomic zones. Zone I: distal to the FDS insertion on the middle phalanx Zone II: between the FDS insertion on the middle phalanx (distally) and the A1 pulley overlying the metacarpophalangeal (MP) joint (proximally) Zone III: between the A1 pulley over the MP joint (distally) and the distal extent of the carpal tunnel (proximally) Zone IV: within the carpal tunnel Zone V: proximal to the carpal tunnel Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-20. Zones of flexor tendon injuries on the fingers, thumb, and hand. Extensor tendon injuries are categorized into nine anatomic zones. Zone I: over the DIP joint Zone II: over the middle phalanx Zone III: over

the PIP joint Zone IV: over the proximal phalanx Zone V: over the MP joint Zone VI: over the metacarpal Zone VII: over the carpus Zone VIII: over the distal forearm and extensor retinaculum Zone IX: over the proximal forearm Preoperative Preparation In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to describe the concept and use of a tendon graft, two-stage repair, or tendon transfer required when direct repair is not optimal. Single-stage tendon graft reconstruction requires an adequate tendon sheath. The palmaris longus is a commonly used donor tendon. If the tendon sheath is absent or scarred, two-stage reconstruction, consisting of silicone rod placement and pseudosheath formation followed by tendon grafting, may be necessary. Tendon transfer may be required if the proximal muscle is nonfunctional. Key Steps of the Procedure In a patient with a flexor or extensor tendon injury, be able to demonstrate the variety of operative incisions required to gain access to perform the repair. Midlateral or Bruner (zigzag) incisions are typically used, incorporating existing skin lacerations when possible and optimizing access to both tendon ends. Avoiding incisions that cross flexion creases perpendicularly minimizes flexion contracture formation. In a patient with a flexor or extensor tendon injury, be able to describe the characteristics of suture techniques required for an effective tendon repair. Key common features include the following: At least four core suture strands across the repair Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-22. Technique of performing a four-strand flexor tendon core suture repair is demonstrated in association with a peripheral running suture. An epitendinous suture layer when the repair must pass through the pulley mechanism Intraoperative Decision Making In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to demonstrate the appropriate suture choice and technique required for successful repair. Tendon repairs are typically performed using braided permanent sutures. Key principles include the following: Minimizing tendon handling Placing sutures about 1 cm from the tendon ends Ensuring proper tendon orientation Minimizing the bulk of the repair Ensuring strength of repair with no gapping Confirming smooth gliding within the tendon sheath (when present) Complications and their Treatment In a patient who has undergone flexor tendon repair, be able to recognize repair rupture and formulate a plan for correction required to achieve satisfactory outcome. Repair rupture often presents as an acute “pop” with recurrence of presenting symptom (eg, loss of flexion or extension, depending on the tendon repaired). In the case of rupture, exploration and repeat repair are generally recommended. Long-term Follow-up Following tendon repair, be able to measure active, passive, and total range of motion required for following and documenting progress. Passive range of motion refers to motion that can be achieved through manipulating the joints with no effort from the patient. Active range of motion is that achieved with the patient's using his or her own muscles without assistance. Normal joint motions: Normal MP joint motion: 0 degrees of extension to 90 degrees of flexion Normal PIP joint motion: 5 degrees of hyperextension to 110 degrees of flexion Normal DIP joint motion: 30 degrees of hyperextension to 90 degrees of flexion In a patient who has undergone successful tendon repair, be able to recognize the indications and prerequisites for further surgery required to obtain optimal results. Stiffness is common following tendon repair. Extensive hand therapy resulting in maximal passive range of motion is critical prior to undertaking tenolysis to improve active range of motion.

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries COMMON EPA April 16, 2025 Ian Kratzke, MD • Jared Robert Gallaher, MD, MPH Based on a previous module by Rafael Torres-Fajardo, MD; Edgardo Salcedo, MD; and Gregory Jurkovich, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy Thorax The neurovascular bundle runs inferior to the rib. It is essential to be aware of this relationship when performing a thoracotomy, tube thoracostomy, rib fixation, or nerve block to avoid damage to these structures. Rapid identification of the angle of Louis (sternomanubrial joint) serves as a landmark to identify the second intercostal space for needle decompression of tension pneumothorax. Diaphragm The diaphragm has 3 major foramina, allowing the passage of the inferior vena cava at level T8, the esophagus at T10, and the aorta at T12. The phrenic vein is located 1 cm above the esophageal hiatus. Injury to this vein can result in significant bleeding. The phrenic nerve arises at C3, C4, and C5. It runs through the posterolateral mediastinum to the caudal surface of the diaphragm. It gives rise to 4 branches spreading centrifugally, 1 anteriorly, 1 posteriorly, and 2 laterally. The location of the diaphragm is highly variable relative to the chest wall, so it is important to avoid placing chest tubes too low. Typically, a chest tube is placed at the anterior axillary line between the fourth and fifth intercostal space to avoid intra-abdominal placement. Physiology Pleura During penetrating chest trauma, air enters the thoracic cavity, either from a hole in the lung or from the outside. The potential space between the visceral and parietal peritoneum becomes real, and the lung collapses due to its elastic recoil, causing a pneumothorax. During blunt trauma, rib fractures can lacerate the lung. In addition, a sudden increase in intrathoracic pressure (direct blow, violent coughing) can result in alveolar rupture, leading to an air leak and pneumothorax. Injury to the chest may also result in pulmonary contusion because of the physical transfer of energy, leading to edema and hemorrhage of the lung. Physiologically, this causes hypoxemia from an increased shunt (blood flow to a nonaerated lung) and can also lead to carbon dioxide retention and respiratory acidosis due to the altered work of breathing. Diaphragm Blunt diaphragmatic injuries result from crush or blunt abdominal trauma when intra-abdominal pressure is increased. This increased pressure causes an increase in the pleuroperitoneal gradient, tearing the muscle. Given the high energy required to rupture the diaphragm, other associated injuries, such as hemothorax, pneumothorax, rib fractures, and splenic injuries, are common. Penetrating trauma, in contrast, causes short tears. Sternum Patients with sternal fractures caused by high-impact chest trauma can present with other associated injuries, including rib fractures, pulmonary contusions, and cardiac contusions. These patients are also at increased risk for extrathoracic injuries, including spinal fractures and cranial injuries. Diagnosis: Physical Findings Pneumothorax Patients with a pneumothorax can present either with or without symptoms. Physical findings include: Hypoxia Subcutaneous emphysema Decreased breath sounds Tension pneumothorax presents with: Hypotension Jugular venous distention (JVD) Tracheal deviation to the opposite side of the pneumothorax Cardiac tamponade Patients with cardiac tamponade may present with hypotension,

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: JVD, and muffled heart sounds (Beck's triad). Fractures Patients with rib fractures may have pain, chest wall hemorrhage, crepitus, and chest wall instability. Flail chest is the term for multiple consecutive segmentally fractured ribs (at least three or more) causing delayed or asymmetrical rise in the affected chest wall. Some patients may present with actual paradoxical chest wall movement, but this is not required to make the diagnosis. Diaphragmatic injury In penetrating chest trauma, injury should be suspected in any trauma below the nipple. In addition, a diaphragm injury could be present in patients with hemothorax or pneumothorax and known liver or spleen injury. In blunt trauma, diaphragmatic injury should be suspected in high-velocity and quick deceleration events and blunt abdominal trauma. This injury is difficult to diagnose with a physical examination. Diagnosis: Imaging Hemothorax In chest trauma, it is important to understand how to identify a complete opacification or “white lung” and the need to place a chest tube. The presence of blood or fluid may cause compression and deviation of the mediastinal structures to the contralateral side. This contrasts with lung collapse, in which structures deviate toward the affected lung. In the supine position, chest x-ray (CXR) reveals hemothorax when 200 to 300 mL of blood is present. Pneumothorax On CXR, patients with pneumothorax will not have lung markings extending to the edge of the ribs. A tension pneumothorax is a clinical rather than radiological diagnosis as it indicates that a patient is hypotensive from loss of venous return to the heart due to compression from the pneumothorax. There may also be a component of hemothorax in patients with concomitant pneumothorax. Sensitivity for pneumothorax on CXR is increased when the patient is placed in an upright position. CXR interpretation includes evaluation of: Degree of penetration Abnormalities of lung parenchyma and pleura (lung expansion, contusion, pneumothoraces, and hemothoraces) Abnormalities of the trachea and bronchi Position of endotracheal tube and lines Presence of rib or bone fractures Ultrasound is another useful adjunct and is more sensitive than CXR in visualizing small hemothoraces and pneumothoraces. CT remains the gold standard for detecting small pneumothoraces. When a pneumothorax is demonstrated on CT but not CXR, it is considered an “occult” pneumothorax. Aortic injury In the National Trauma Data Bank, aortic injury was present in only 0.3% of patients sustaining blunt trauma, although the associated mortality exceeds 37%. CXR The most sensitive indicator of blunt aortic injury is an abnormal or widened mediastinum (> 6 cm on an upright posteroanterior CXR; > 8 cm or > 25% of transthoracic diameter at the level of the aortic arch on a supine anteroposterior CXR). Other findings of mediastinal hematoma include left apical cap, right tracheal shift or right enteric tube shift, inferior displacement of left mainstem bronchus, and blunting of aortic knob. Most signs are present in 30% to 70% of patients. Only 12.5% of mediastinal hematomas result from aortic injury. However, the negative predictive value of a normal CXR of high quality is approximately 97%, but this may reflect the low incidence of blunt thoracic aortic injury. First rib fracture indicates severe trauma and the possibility of traumatic aortic injury (15%–30% frequency). Cardiac echocardiography to evaluate for tamponade is a part of the FAST exam.

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: Contrast CT is the most sensitive exam for aortic injury and helps grade the severity of the injury. Fractures CXR Rib fractures may be difficult to identify on plain film unless significantly displaced. Clavicular fractures are more easily identified on CXR. CT CT helps differentiate between pleural fluid collections and parenchymal injury in stable patients, as seen in pulmonary contusions. CT is more sensitive than CXR in the detection of rib and sternal fractures. CT of the thoracic spine is the gold standard for assessing vertebral body and posterior element fractures. Diaphragmatic injury CXR Flattening of the diaphragm or the presence of a nasogastric tube or gastric bubble in the left hemithorax is indicative of diaphragmatic injury. CT CT is more sensitive than CXR in identifying a diaphragmatic injury, but one may still not be evident, especially if it is right-sided as the liver may obscure the defect. If a diaphragmatic injury is suspected (eg, thoracoabdominal injuries), despite negative imaging findings, laparotomy, diagnostic laparoscopy, or video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS) should be performed. Operative Management Hemothorax/pneumothorax The treatment goal for hemothorax and pneumothorax is evacuation of the pleural space and re-expansion of the lung. This is done by tube thoracostomy, followed by CXR to verify the position of the chest tube. After completion of tube thoracostomy for hemothorax, the chest tube must be monitored. Emergent thoracotomy is suggested when the initial output is 1 L of blood or there is continued chest output of 200 mL/h for 4 hours. If hemothoraces remain after chest tube drainage or if there are persistent air leaks with pneumothoraces, VATS may be required to wash out retained hemothorax or intervene on a persistent bronchial injury with the possibility of a lung resection. Fractures Indications for operative fixation of rib fractures: Severely displaced fractures in patients undergoing thoracotomies for associated intrathoracic injuries Progressive deterioration of pulmonary function despite aggressive nonoperative pain management Pulmonary contusions and associated rib fractures in patients who are unable to be weaned from the ventilator after contusions have resolved Significant chest wall deformity and nonunion of fractures Indications for operative fixation of sternal fractures include: Unstable fractures Fractures associated with infection Fractures can be repaired with plates, intramedullary devices, vertical bridging prostheses, and sternal wires. Chronic pain Diaphragmatic injury Acute diaphragmatic injuries are best repaired through the abdomen. This approach allows the evaluation of other associated intra-abdominal injuries. The best approach for chronic diaphragmatic injuries is through the thorax. Operative steps include debridement of obviously necrotic tissue, eversion of borders for adequate approximation (when primary repair is feasible) either with stay sutures or an Allis clamp, the use of nonabsorbable sutures, and interrupted or running suture primary repair (surgeon preference). Injury to the phrenic nerve should be avoided. When a central defect does not allow primary tension-free repair, there are 2 options: The peripheral attachments can be incised anteriorly, laterally, and posteriorly from their costal origins to close the defect, and the diaphragm is reattached 2 to 3 interspaces more cephalad. The defect can be repaired with biological or synthetic mesh material. Nonoperative Management Patients with chest trauma require early pain control with multimodal pain regimens, as they often have poor inspiratory effort and splinting, leading to hypoventilation, atelectasis, pneumonia (due to retained secretions), and respiratory failure. Respiratory support with mechanical ventilation

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: for several days is sometimes required to manage significant pulmonary contusion and flail chest. Aggressive pulmonary toilet, incentive spirometry, adequate analgesia, and multimodal pain management are critical in the nonoperative management of these patients. Pain management consists of: IV medications (opioids, ketorolac), which are essential for early pain control Oral medications (eg, NSAIDs, acetaminophen, opioids, gabapentin, muscle relaxants), which are critical for long-term pain control Epidural analgesia Elastomeric pumps, which automatically and continuously deliver a regulated flow of local anesthetic via a subcutaneous-paravertebral catheter Understanding the venous plasma concentration of local anesthetic agents and their clinical implications is vital.

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Tony Boualoy, MD • Alexandra Helbing, MD • Eric Schupp, MD • Samantha Sherman, MD • Kevin Y. Pei, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomic Considerations In penetrating trauma to the neck, cervical blood vessels are the most commonly injured structures. Zones of the neck are: Zone III: angle of mandible to skull base Zone II: cricothyroid to angle of mandible. Penetrating injuries occur most frequently in this zone (47%). Zone I: sternal notch to cricothyroid The vertebral artery is made up of four segments. Injuries to this artery occur in less than 1% of all trauma admissions. V4 (intradural or intracranial): extends from the dura mater to their confluence to form the basilar artery V3 (atlantic; extradural or extraspinal): extends from C2 to the dura mater. It is the most commonly injured segment in basilar skull fracture. V2 (foraminal): extends from the transverse foramen of C6 to the transverse foramen of C2 V1 (preforaminal): extends from vertebral artery origin off the subclavian artery to the transverse foramen of C6 Key anatomic structures of the neck are discussed in more detail in the SCORE module Initial Diagnosis and Management of Neck Trauma. Epidemiology and Etiology The incidence of blunt cerebrovascular injury (BCVI) in trauma patients is 1% to 2%. Motor vehicle crashes are a major cause of BCVIs. Many injuries occur when a blood vessel is stretched over the cervical vertebrae. This results in damage to the tunica intima. Hyperextension and rotation are important mechanisms in BCVI. The incidence of penetrating neck wounds in trauma patients is approximately 10%. In patients presenting with penetrating neck injuries, it is important to determine the mechanism of penetration as this may provide insight into the extent of tissue damage and guide diagnostic and therapeutic options. Vascular injuries are the most common type of cervical injuries and are associated with up to 40% of complications related to penetrating neck injuries, with approximately 10% of patients suffering injuries to the carotid artery. The mortality rate for penetrating neck injuries is estimated to range from 3-6%, with 50% of deaths associated with hemorrhage secondary to vascular injuries. Direct trauma, such as basilar skull fractures or injuries caused by seat belts, may result in cerebrovascular injuries. Initial Screening All patients who present with neurologic deficit or epistaxis from a suspected arterial injury should be screened for BCVI. Cerebral angiography or a CT angiography using a 16-slice CT scanner should be used. The Denver and Memphis criteria are two protocols that are used to identify patients at high risk for BCVI who should undergo further testing. Denver criteria Signs and symptoms Arterial hemorrhage Cervical bruit (in patients < 50 years of age) Expanding cervical hematoma Focal neurologic deficit Neurologic examination incongruous with CT scan findings Stroke on secondary CT scan Risk factors High-energy transfer mechanism with Le Fort fracture type II or III Base of skull fracture involving the carotid canal Diffuse axonal injury with Glasgow Coma Scale score less than 6 Cervical spine fractures that involve C1 to C3 or the transverse foramen Cervical spine subluxation Near-hanging with hypoxic-ischemic brain injury Memphis criteria Base of skull fracture with involvement of carotid canal Base of skull fracture with involvement of petrous temporal bone Cervical spine fracture Neurologic examination findings not explained by neuroimaging Horner syndrome Le Fort II or III fracture pattern Presence of neck soft tissue injury (seat belt sign, hanging, hematoma) Further Diagnostic Testing

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: Formal angiography is the diagnostic gold standard for vascular injury to the neck, whether blunt or penetrating, although it is rarely needed. The most common method of diagnosis is the multislice CT angiogram, which is the most reliable noninvasive screening modality. The risk of stroke following a formal cerebral angiogram is 1%. Although arterial duplex ultrasound may be used to visualize vascular structures in zone II of the neck, its utility in evaluation of zone I is limited due to the presence of bony structures. The Biffl classification of cerebrovascular injury is a widely accepted grading scheme for BCVI: Grade I: mild initial injury or irregular intima Grade II: dissection with raised intimal flap, intramural hematoma with luminal narrowing greater than 25%, intraluminal thrombosis Grade III: pseudoaneurysm Grade IV: vessel occlusion/thrombosis Grade V: vessel transection with active extravasation Nonoperative Management If there is risk of impending airway obstruction on initial evaluation, such as in the case of an expanding neck hematoma, the airway must be secured. This may involve the use of fiberoptic endotracheal intubation for enhanced visualization of the airway in the setting of external compression resulting from the expanding hematoma. If attempts at endotracheal intubation are unsuccessful, emergency cricothyroidotomy may be warranted. Bedside probing or exploration of open neck wounds, which may disrupt existing clot and result in emboli and/or rebleeding, should be avoided. Patients with Biffl grade I, II, and III cerebrovascular injuries: Antithrombotic therapy (heparin or antiplatelet therapy) should be used for all patients with BCVI, unless contraindicated. Anticoagulation decreases the risk of thromboembolic stroke. Heparin is preferred in the acute setting because of its reversible properties. Current guidelines from the Eastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma recommend against routine use of endovascular stents as an adjunct to antithrombotic therapy in patients with grade II or III BCVIs. CT angiography should be used as a follow-up imaging modality and performed 7 to 10 days after the initial identification of a grade I, II, or III injury to evaluate injury progression or resolution. Operative Treatment Various techniques can be used for repair of carotid artery injuries. The selected technique should take into consideration the extent of the injury, its location, exposure, and the presence or likelihood of infection. The artery should be dissected and mobilized to enable a tension-free repair using running permanent monofilament suture with end-to-end anastomosis. Injuries that are more extensive will likely require repair using either patch angioplasty or an interposition graft. If vein grafting is not an option, prosthetic material such as polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) should be considered. For dirty wounds, autologous venous grafts, such as a saphenous vein interposition graft, is preferred due to the lower risk of infection compared with prosthetic material. Cephalic vein patch repair is generally avoided because it is relatively weak and may result in “blow out” of the patch. In the case of severe injury to the external carotid artery, surgical ligation may be performed with limited morbidity and should be considered in the setting of hemodynamic instability. However, for patients who are hemodynamically stable, ligation of the internal or common carotid arteries should be avoided because of the high risk of severe neurologic sequelae. However, if imaging reveals evidence of a completed stroke secondary to vascular injury and no back-bleeding is observed on exploration, ligation of the damaged internal carotid artery may mitigate the risk of hemorrhagic conversion. Zone I and Zone III injuries in stable patients are

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: best treated with endovascular methods. However, such methods are unsuitable for unstable patients. In unstable patients with Zone I injuries, the best exposure is via a median sternotomy with possible extension to the anterior neck. Open exposure of the proximal great vessels: A median sternotomy provides access to the proximal right subclavian, innominate, and proximal left carotid arteries. A left anterolateral thoracotomy provides access to the proximal left subclavian artery. Extension of a median sternotomy incision to the anterior neck can provide additional exposure of the carotid artery. A supraclavicular incision can be used to gain access to the right subclavian artery and the distal left subclavian artery. A “trap door” incision (left anterolateral thoracotomy, partial sternotomy, and left supraclavicular incision) can be used to gain additional access to the left subclavian artery. This approach is generally avoided due to its associated morbidity. It is necessary to expose the carotid artery for a zone II injury. The patient should be supine on the operating table with the head extended and contralateral to the stab wound. An incision is made anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. The platysma muscle is divided, and the sternocleidomastoid muscle is moved laterally. The medial border of the internal jugular vein is identified and dissected from the surrounding tissues. The facial vein is identified, ligated, then transected. The internal jugular vein is moved laterally. It is important to note if there is concomitant injury to this vein. If the injury is small, then primary closure can be considered for the internal jugular vein. If the injury is large and the only source of bleeding, then formal reconstruction can be appropriate. If the injury is large and the carotid injury requires exposure, the best approach is to simply ligate the internal jugular vein. The carotid artery is exposed. The vagus nerve lies posterior, lateral to the carotid artery. The hypoglossal nerve can also be found in the distal portion of the incision. Injury to the vagus nerve can result in hoarseness, loss of cough reflex (the afferent limb of the vagus nerve innervates multiple laryngotracheal and pharyngoesophageal structures), and dysphagia.
